	<TextRegion id="r7" orientation="0.00000" readingOrientation="0.00000" readingDirection="left-to-right" type="paragraph" indented="false" primaryLanguage="English" primaryScript="Latn - Latin">
	<Coords points="251,1608 1169,1608 1169,1759 808,1759 808,1871 809,1871 809,1917 807,1917 807,1970 806,1970 806,2027 808,2027 808,2073 807,2073 807,2130 809,2130 809,2177 808,2177 808,2218 432,2218 432,2282 199,2282 199,2236 201,2236 201,2117 200,2117 200,2078 201,2078 201,1923 202,1923 202,1696 201,1696 201,1661 251,1661"/>
	<TextEquiv>
	<Unicode>The mobile Web represents a fundamentally dif-
ferent information medium from the traditional Web
in terms of access devices used, content availability,
bandwidth, and cost to the end
user. These differences suggest
there may be little to learn about
mobile Web usage from observa-
tions of regular Web use. In fact,
the reverse is the case; irrespective
of these differences, the same
Universal Law of Web Surfing
applies in both Web and mobile
Web surfing.</Unicode></TextEquiv>
